cts of the festival as celebrated in diverse regions of South Asia and in the South Asian diaspora, this book addresses the following common questions: What does this festival do? What does it achieve, and how? Why and in what way does it sometimes fail? How do mass communication and social media increase participation in and contribute to the changing nature of the festival? The contributors address these questions from multiple perspectives and discuss issues of agency, authority, ritual efficacy, change, appropriation, and adaptation. Because of the festival's reach beyond its diverse celebrations in South Asia, its influence can be seen in the rituals and dances in many parts of Western Europe and North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aDasara. 0aDurgā-pūjā (Hindu festival)xSocial aspectsvCongresses. 0aDurgā-pūjā (Hindu festival). 0aDurgā-pūjā (Hindu festival). 0aHindu godsvCongresses. 0aPuja (Hinduism)vCongresses. 0aWorship (Hinduism)vCongresses. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Ethnography. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aHüsken, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHüsken, Ute, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLunde Ilkama, Ina Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarayanan, Vasudha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOrtegren, Jennifer D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodrigues, Hillary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaul, R. Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https:/